,Recommended,433950,29393605,Posted: 21 January,all,Capt_Blakhelm,"Bit Blaster XL is a VERY straightforward and simple shootem up that is similar to Asteroids with power ups and different ships purchasable from picked up coins. I think BBXL recieved Overwhelmingly Positive reviews not because it is an excellent game, but because it is a simple, but solid, shmup that doesn't intend to do much and does nothing wrong outside of the key rebindings, and it's only $1 or less on sale.- Clean 8 Bit graphics that can make for some nice gifs when there is alot of screen activity- Repetitive chiptune soundtrack - there are apparently about 10 or more tracks in the free DLC soundtrack, but i only heard one song constantly looping-The ship automatically moves, so you simply must turn it left or right - no strafing.- Buttons: Meter limited boosting mechanic, breaking mechanic, fire button (if playing without Auto Fire, which I prefer to save ammo), and screen clearing bomb buttons.- Arena: A enclosed rectangle where the walls will kill you. Incoming asteroids are hinted by light shafts for strategic feedback.- Asteroids drop ammo pick ups for your base weapons and weapon pickups (short range destrucive laser, 3 way shot, short range spread, bomb shot, piercing laser and a couple more)- Besides Asteroids, there are missles that occasionaly shot single bullets, or rockets that explode into multiple bullets, and I've only encountered one ""chasing"" enemy type, but there might be more if you can get further in the game.- Coins occasionally drop which can be used to buy ships that have different armor, shooting, speed, and bomb attributes.And you basically keep shooting asteroids and enemies until you die. Options screen is simplistic as SFX, Music and Vibrate can only be turned off and on with out any sliders/incrementation.Besides the repeating soundtrack, my biggest problem is the lack of easily rebindable keys. Custom inputs made a HUGE difference in my ability to play well and trying to rebind them is cumbersome. You can only rebind them in a Unity game launcher if you hold ALT when you open the game (which is the first time I've ever had to do that for a Steam game - WTF?) and the keys are labeled as their Xbox buttons and not as their in game function - so you need to memorize the keys or just guess. This launcher also can only recognize Trigger inputs as Axes, so you can only rebind them to an actual joystick Analogue stick or trigger button instead of a keyboard-thankfully, I don't think you need them and the face buttons can be mapped to a keyboard.It certainly isn't a a must play and I'm not personally crazy about it - but it might be worth going back to with better controls."
