,Recommended,433950,20877889,"Posted: 31 January, 2016",all,blokkemblokkem,"*April 16 UPDATE*Just the fact that the developer continued to reach out for 1 customers personal opinion gives me hope that the future of gaming isn't entirely doomed.  More devs should follow suit.The addition of two game modes supporting both auto fire and non-auto fire is such a simple thing, but it makes a huge difference by giving the player the option.  I found the selective firing method provided a gaming experience that made me feel much more in control of the game rather than before where it was just a monotonous exercise in moving around.  You can time your shots and WAIT for enemies to position based on the type of special powerups you have now.  Originally the simple premise of the game was part of its charm, but also highlighted some flaws.  Putting the timing of movement and firing back in the player's control adds that little strategy that was missing before.For the price, now I would definitely recommend this game.*Original Review below (Negative)*I like the concept of the game, but after about 45 minutes, you'll have all the achievements (except the higher score ones) and nothing else to do.  Even something as simple as some score multipliers would keep the game fresh a little longer.  With that said, the thing that needs the most work is the auto-shooting.I'm not entirely opposed to the auto-shooting mechanic.  I mean, it's the developers game so it's his/her choice, but one thing that is unsatisfactory about it is the fact that as soon as you press ""start"" to begin a game, there about 5-6 enemies that slowly spawn over about 30 seconds, but your ship is forced to shoot off in the distance for what boils down to probably a 10% accuracy rate simply because there is nothing to shoot.Now, no one cares about accuracy, it's not even a stat to track in this game, but I bring it up because of the simple fact that there is no DEFAULT unlimited ammo so when you run out of ammo (because you're forced to shoot into the void remember?), you simply STOP SHOOTING.  That's it.  The game is a SHOOTER!What should happen is one of two things:1.  If you have a special weapon and run out of that type of ammo, your ship should default to regular unlimited bullets.2.  If you don't have a special weapon, you should never run out of the default bullets.  (Think Contra for the NES).I'll change my review if the default bullet issue is addressed.  It's just not fun.  Even for $0.99."
